{"type":"message","id":"1a49a8ec","parentId":"1745096b","timestamp":"2026-04-10T05:58:51.262Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_ir9ve05r330m_1","toolName":"web_crawl","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"url\": \"https://github.com/walkinglabs/learn-harness-engineering\",\n  \"content\": \"sanbuphy\\n.github/workflows\\n.github/workflows\\nAdd mermaid diagrams to all lectures, PDF build pipeline, and README …\\ndocs\\ndocs\\nrefactor: move .opencode/skills to top-level skills/, remove skill-cr…\\nprojects\\nprojects\\nUpdate lectures, add code examples, and enhance docs\\nscripts\\nscripts\\nAdd mermaid diagrams to all lectures, PDF build pipeline, and README …\\nskills\\nskills\\nrefactor: move .opencode/skills to top-level skills/, remove skill-cr…\\n.gitignore\\n.gitignore\\nAdd mermaid diagrams to all lectures, PDF build pipeline, and README …\\nCLAUDE.md\\nCLAUDE.md\\nUpdate acknowledgments wording and refresh CLAUDE.md\\nREADME-CN.md\\nREADME-CN.md\\ndocs: refine README visual preview descriptions based on actual scree…\\nREADME.md\\nREADME.md\\ndocs: refine README visual preview descriptions based on actual scree…\\nget_anthropic_logo.js\\nget_anthropic_logo.js\\nAdd mermaid diagrams to all lectures, PDF build pipeline, and README …\\npackage-lock.json\\npackage-lock.json\\nAdd mermaid diagrams to all lectures, PDF build pipeline, and README …\\nApr 2, 2026\\npackage.json\\npackage.json\\nAdd mermaid diagrams to all lectures, PDF build pipeline, and README …\\nApr 2, 2026\\nREADME\\nLearn Harness Engineering\\nA project-based course on building the environment, state management, verification, and control mechanisms that make AI coding agents work reliably.\\nLearn Harness Engineering is a course dedicated to the engineering of AI coding agents. We have deeply studied and synthesized the most advanced Harness Engineering theories and practices in the industry. Our core references include:\\nOpenAI: Harness engineering: leveraging Codex in an agent-first world\\nAnthropic: Effective harnesses for long-running agents\\nAnthropic: Harness design for long-running application development\\nAwesome Harness Engineering\\nWebsite & Docs (English & 中文) | 中文 README\\nQuick start? The skills/harness-creator/ skill can help you scaffold a production-grade harness (AGENTS.md, feature lists, init.sh, verification workflows) for your own project in minutes.\\n✨ Visual Preview\\n🏠 Course Homepage\\nA comprehensive course outline and introduction to core philosophies, providing a clear path to get started.\\n📖 Immersive Lectures\\nDeep dives into real-world pain points and hands-on projects (like Project 01) for an immersive learning experience.\\n🗂️ Ready-to-Use Resource Library\\nTemplates and reference configurations designed to solve common pitfalls in multi-turn AI agent development, such as context loss and premature task completion.\\nPDF Coursebooks\\nThe repository now includes a PDF build pipeline for the course content.\\nRun npm run pdf:build to generate English and Chinese PDFs locally.\\nOutput files are written to artifacts/pdfs/.\\nRun npm run screenshots:readme if you want to refresh the README preview images.\\nGitHub Actions workflow release-course-pdfs.yml can build the PDFs and publish them to GitHub Releases.\\nThe Model Is Smart, The Harness Makes It Reliable\\nThere's a hard truth most people learn the hard way: the strongest model in the world will still fail on real engineering tasks if you don't build a proper environment around it.\\nYou've probably seen this yourself. You give Claude or GPT a task in your repo. It starts well — reads files, writes code, looks productive. Then something goes wrong. It skips a step. It breaks a test. It says \\\"done\\\" but nothing actually works. You spend more time cleaning up than if you'd done it yourself.\\nThis isn't a model problem. It's a harness problem.\\nThe evidence is clear. Anthropic ran a controlled experiment: same model (Opus 4.5), same prompt (\\\"build a 2D retro game editor\\\"). Without a harness, it spent $9 in 20 minutes and produced something that didn't work. With a full harness (planner + generator + evaluator), it spent $200 in 6 hours and built a game you could actually play. The model didn't change. The harness did.\\nOpenAI reported the same thing with Codex: in a well-harnessed repository, the same model goes from \\\"unreliable\\\" to \\\"reliable.\\\" Not a marginal improvement — a qualitative shift.\\nThis course teaches you how to build that environment.\\nTHE HARNESS PATTERN\\n                    ====================\\n\\n    You --> give task --> Agent reads harness files --> Agent executes\\n                                                        |\\n                                              harness governs every step:\\n                                              |\\n                                              +--> Instructions: what to do, in what order\\n                                              +--> Scope:       one feature at a time, no overreach\\n                                              +--> State:       progress log, feature list, git history\\n                                              +--> Verification: tests, lint, type-check, smoke runs\\n                                              +--> Lifecycle:   init at start, clean state at end\\n                                              |\\n                                              v\\n                                         Agent stops only when\\n                                         verification passes\\nWhat Harness Engineering Actually Means\\nHarness engineering is about building a complete working environment around the model so it produces reliable results. It's not about writing better prompts. It's about designing the system the model operates inside.\\nA harness has five subsystems:\\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\\n    │                        THE HARNESS                              │\\n    │                                                                 │\\n    │   ┌──────────────┐  ┌──────────────┐  ┌──────────────────────┐ │\\n    │   │ Instructions  │  │    State     │  │   Verification       │ │\\n    │   │              │  │              │  │                      │ │\\n    │   │ AGENTS.md    │  │ progress.md  │  │ tests + lint         │ │\\n    │   │ CLAUDE.md    │  │ feature_list │  │ type-check           │ │\\n    │   │ feature_list │  │ git log      │  │ smoke runs           │ │\\n    │   │ docs/        │  │ session hand │  │ e2e pipeline         │ │\\n    │   └──────────────┘  └──────────────┘  └──────────────────────┘ │\\n    │                                                                 │\\n    │   ┌──────────────┐  ┌──────────────────────────────────────┐   │\\n    │   │    Scope     │  │         Session Lifecycle             │   │\\n    │   │              │  │                                      │   │\\n    │   │ one feature  │  │ init.sh at start                     │   │\\n    │   │ at a time   │  │ clean-state checklist at end          │   │\\n    │   │ definition   │  │ handoff note for next session        │   │\\n    │   │ of done      │  │ commit only when safe to resume      │   │\\n    │   └──────────────┘  └──────────────────────────────────────┘   │\\n    │                                                                 │\\n    └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\\n\\n    The MODEL decides what code to write.\\n    The HARNESS governs when, where, and how it writes it.\\n    The harness doesn't make the model smarter.\\n    It makes the model's output reliable.\\nEach subsystem has one job:\\nInstructions — Tell the agent what to do, in what order, and what to read before starting. Not one giant file; a progressive disclosure structure the agent navigates on demand.\\nState — Track what's been done, what's in progress, and what's next. Persisted to disk so the next session picks up exactly where the last one left off.\\nVerification — Only a passing test suite counts as evidence. The agent cannot declare victory without runnable proof.\\nScope — Constrain the agent to one feature at a time. No overreach. No half-finishing three things. No rewriting the feature list to hide unfinished work.\\nSession Lifecycle — Initialize at the start. Clean up at the end. Leave a clean restart path for the next session.\\nWhy This Course Exists\\nThe question isn't \\\"can models write code?\\\" They can. The question is: can they reliably complete real engineering tasks inside real repositories, over multiple sessions, without constant human supervision?\\nRight now, the answer is: not without a harness.\\nWITHOUT HARNESS                          WITH HARNESS\\n    ==============                          ============\\n\\n    Session 1: agent writes code            Session 1: agent reads instructions\\n              agent breaks tests                      agent runs init.sh\\n              agent says \\\"done\\\"                       agent works on one feature\\n              you fix it manually                     agent verifies before claiming done\\n                                                       agent updates progress log\\n    Session 2: agent starts fresh                    agent commits clean state\\n              agent has no memory\\n              of what happened before         Session 2: agent reads progress log\\n              agent re-does work                       agent picks up exactly where it left off\\n              or does something else entirely          agent continues the unfinished feature\\n              you fix it again                         you review, not rescue\\n\\n    Result: you spend more time                  Result: agent does the work,\\n            cleaning up than if you                      you verify the result\\n            did it yourself\\nThe questions this course actually cares about:\\nWhich harness designs improve task completion rates?\\nWhich designs reduce rework and incorrect completions?\\nWhich mechanisms keep long-running tasks progressing steadily?\\nWhich structures keep the system maintainable after multiple agent runs?\\nCourse Curriculum & Documentation\\nFor the full course materials, please visit the Documentation Website .\\nThe curriculum is divided into three parts:\\nLectures : 12 conceptual units explaining the theory behind harness engineering.\\nProjects : 6 hands-on projects where you build an agentic workspace from scratch.\\nResource Library : Copy-ready templates (AGENTS.md, feature_list.json, init.sh, etc.) to use in your own repositories today.\\nQuick Start: Improve Your Agent Today\\nYou don't need to read all 12 lectures before you start getting value. If you're already using a coding agent on a real project, here's how to improve it right now.\\nThe idea is simple: instead of just writing prompts, give your agent a set of structured files that define what to do, what's been done, and how to verify the work. These files live inside your repo, so every session starts from the same state.\\nYOUR PROJECT ROOT\\n    ├── AGENTS.md              <-- the agent's operating manual\\n    ├── CLAUDE.md              <-- (alternative, if using Claude Code)\\n    ├── init.sh                <-- runs install + verify + start\\n    ├── feature_list.json      <-- what features exist, which are done\\n    ├── claude-progress.md     <-- what happened each session\\n    └── src/                   <-- your actual code\\nGrab the starter templates from the Resource Library and drop them into your project. That's it. Four files, and your agent sessions will already be significantly more stable than running on prompts alone.\\nCapstone Project: A Real App\\nAll six course projects revolve around the same product: an Electron-based personal knowledge base desktop app.\\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\\n    │               Knowledge Base Desktop App            │\\n    │                                                     │\\n    │  ┌──────────────┐  ┌──────────────────────────────┐│\\n    │  │ Document List │  │       Q&A Panel              ││\\n    │  │              │  │                              ││\\n    │  │ doc-001.md   │  │  Q: What is harness eng?    ││\\n    │  │ doc-002.md   │  │  A: The environment built    ││\\n    │  │ doc-003.md   │  │     around an agent model... ││\\n    │  │ ...          │  │     [citation: doc-002.md]   ││\\n    │  └──────────────┘  └──────────────────────────────┘│\\n    │                                                     │\\n    │  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐│\\n    │  │ Status Bar: 42 docs | 38 indexed | last sync 3m ││\\n    │  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘│\\n    └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\\n\\n    Core features:\\n    ├── Import local documents\\n    ├── Manage a document library\\n    ├── Process and index documents\\n    ├── Run AI-powered Q&A over imported content\\n    └── Return grounded answers with citations\\nThis project was chosen because it combines strong practical value, enough real-world product complexity, and a good setting for observing before/after harness improvements.\\nEach course project's starter/solution is a complete copy of this Electron app at that evolutionary stage. P(N+1)'s starter is derived from P(N)'s solution — the app evolves as your harness skills grow.\\nLearning Path\\nThe course is designed to be done in order. Each phase builds on the last.\\nPhase 1: SEE THE PROBLEM              Phase 2: STRUCTURE THE REPO\\n    ========================              ==========================\\n\\n    L01  Strong models ≠ reliable         L03  Repository as single\\n         execution                              source of truth\\n    L02  What harness actually means\\n                                       L04  Split instructions across\\n         |                                   files, not one giant file\\n         v\\n    P01  Prompt-only vs.                       |\\n         rules-first comparison                v\\n                                               P02  Agent-readable workspace\\n\\n\\n    Phase 3: CONNECT SESSIONS             Phase 4: FEEDBACK & SCOPE\\n    ==========================           =========================\\n\\n    L05  Keep context alive               L07  Draw clear task boundaries\\n         across sessions\\n                                       L08  Feature lists as harness\\n    L06  Initialize before every               primitives\\n         agent session\\n                                               |\\n         |                                     v\\n         v                                     P04  Runtime feedback to\\n    P03  Multi-session continuity                   correct agent behavior\\n\\n\\n    Phase 5: VERIFICATION                 Phase 6: PUT IT ALL TOGETHER\\n    =====================                 ============================\\n\\n    L09  Stop agents from                 L11  Make agent's runtime\\n         declaring victory early               observable\\n\\n    L10  Full-pipeline run =              L12  Clean handoff at end of\\n         real verification                      every session\\n\\n         |                                     |\\n         v                                     v\\n    P05  Agent verifies its own work       P06  Build a complete harness\\n                                               (capstone project)\\nEach phase takes about a week if you're going part-time. If you want to go faster, phases 1–3 can be done in a long weekend.\\nSyllabus\\nLectures — 12 conceptual units, each answering one core question\\nRead the full text for each lecture on the Documentation Website.\\nSession Question Core Idea\\nL01 Why do strong models still fail on real tasks? The capability gap between benchmarks and real engineering\\nL02 What does \\\"harness\\\" actually mean? Five subsystems: instructions, state, verification, scope, lifecycle\\nL03 Why must the repo be the single source of truth? If the agent can't see it, it doesn't exist\\nL04 Why does one giant instruction file fail? Progressive disclosure: give a map, not an encyclopedia\\nL05 Why do long-running tasks lose continuity? Persist progress to disk; pick up where you left off\\nL06 Why does initialization need its own phase? Verify the environment is healthy before the agent starts work\\nL07 Why do agents overreach and under-finish? One feature at a time; explicit definition of done\\nL08 Why are feature lists harness primitives? Machine-readable scope boundaries the agent can't ignore\\nL09 Why do agents declare victory too early? Verification gaps:\"\n}"}],"details":{"url":"https://github.com/walkinglabs/learn-harness-engineering","content":"sanbuphy\n.github/workflows\n.github/workflows\nAdd mermaid diagrams to all lectures, PDF build pipeline, and README …\ndocs\ndocs\nrefactor: move .opencode/skills to top-level skills/, remove skill-cr…\nprojects\nprojects\nUpdate lectures, add code examples, and enhance docs\nscripts\nscripts\nAdd mermaid diagrams to all lectures, PDF build pipeline, and README …\nskills\nskills\nrefactor: move .opencode/skills to top-level skills/, remove skill-cr…\n.gitignore\n.gitignore\nAdd mermaid diagrams to all lectures, PDF build pipeline, and README …\nCLAUDE.md\nCLAUDE.md\nUpdate acknowledgments wording and refresh CLAUDE.md\nREADME-CN.md\nREADME-CN.md\ndocs: refine README visual preview descriptions based on actual scree…\nREADME.md\nREADME.md\ndocs: refine README visual preview descriptions based on actual scree…\nget_anthropic_logo.js\nget_anthropic_logo.js\nAdd mermaid diagrams to all lectures, PDF build pipeline, and README …\npackage-lock.json\npackage-lock.json\nAdd mermaid diagrams to all lectures, PDF build pipeline, and README …\nApr 2, 2026\npackage.json\npackage.json\nAdd mermaid diagrams to all lectures, PDF build pipeline, and README …\nApr 2, 2026\nREADME\nLearn Harness Engineering\nA project-based course on building the environment, state management, verification, and control mechanisms that make AI coding agents work reliably.\nLearn Harness Engineering is a course dedicated to the engineering of AI coding agents. We have deeply studied and synthesized the most advanced Harness Engineering theories and practices in the industry. Our core references include:\nOpenAI: Harness engineering: leveraging Codex in an agent-first world\nAnthropic: Effective harnesses for long-running agents\nAnthropic: Harness design for long-running application development\nAwesome Harness Engineering\nWebsite & Docs (English & 中文) | 中文 README\nQuick start? The skills/harness-creator/ skill can help you scaffold a production-grade harness (AGENTS.md, feature lists, init.sh, verification workflows) for your own project in minutes.\n✨ Visual Preview\n🏠 Course Homepage\nA comprehensive course outline and introduction to core philosophies, providing a clear path to get started.\n📖 Immersive Lectures\nDeep dives into real-world pain points and hands-on projects (like Project 01) for an immersive learning experience.\n🗂️ Ready-to-Use Resource Library\nTemplates and reference configurations designed to solve common pitfalls in multi-turn AI agent development, such as context loss and premature task completion.\nPDF Coursebooks\nThe repository now includes a PDF build pipeline for the course content.\nRun npm run pdf:build to generate English and Chinese PDFs locally.\nOutput files are written to artifacts/pdfs/.\nRun npm run screenshots:readme if you want to refresh the README preview images.\nGitHub Actions workflow release-course-pdfs.yml can build the PDFs and publish them to GitHub Releases.\nThe Model Is Smart, The Harness Makes It Reliable\nThere's a hard truth most people learn the hard way: the strongest model in the world will still fail on real engineering tasks if you don't build a proper environment around it.\nYou've probably seen this yourself. You give Claude or GPT a task in your repo. It starts well — reads files, writes code, looks productive. Then something goes wrong. It skips a step. It breaks a test. It says \"done\" but nothing actually works. You spend more time cleaning up than if you'd done it yourself.\nThis isn't a model problem. It's a harness problem.\nThe evidence is clear. Anthropic ran a controlled experiment: same model (Opus 4.5), same prompt (\"build a 2D retro game editor\"). Without a harness, it spent $9 in 20 minutes and produced something that didn't work. With a full harness (planner + generator + evaluator), it spent $200 in 6 hours and built a game you could actually play. The model didn't change. The harness did.\nOpenAI reported the same thing with Codex: in a well-harnessed repository, the same model goes from \"unreliable\" to \"reliable.\" Not a marginal improvement — a qualitative shift.\nThis course teaches you how to build that environment.\nTHE HARNESS PATTERN\n                    ====================\n\n    You --> give task --> Agent reads harness files --> Agent executes\n                                                        |\n                                              harness governs every step:\n                                              |\n                                              +--> Instructions: what to do, in what order\n                                              +--> Scope:       one feature at a time, no overreach\n                                              +--> State:       progress log, feature list, git history\n                                              +--> Verification: tests, lint, type-check, smoke runs\n                                              +--> Lifecycle:   init at start, clean state at end\n                                              |\n                                              v\n                                         Agent stops only when\n                                         verification passes\nWhat Harness Engineering Actually Means\nHarness engineering is about building a complete working environment around the model so it produces reliable results. It's not about writing better prompts. It's about designing the system the model operates inside.\nA harness has five subsystems:\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n    │                        THE HARNESS                              │\n    │                                                                 │\n    │   ┌──────────────┐  ┌──────────────┐  ┌──────────────────────┐ │\n    │   │ Instructions  │  │    State     │  │   Verification       │ │\n    │   │              │  │              │  │                      │ │\n    │   │ AGENTS.md    │  │ progress.md  │  │ tests + lint         │ │\n    │   │ CLAUDE.md    │  │ feature_list │  │ type-check           │ │\n    │   │ feature_list │  │ git log      │  │ smoke runs           │ │\n    │   │ docs/        │  │ session hand │  │ e2e pipeline         │ │\n    │   └──────────────┘  └──────────────┘  └──────────────────────┘ │\n    │                                                                 │\n    │   ┌──────────────┐  ┌──────────────────────────────────────┐   │\n    │   │    Scope     │  │         Session Lifecycle             │   │\n    │   │              │  │                                      │   │\n    │   │ one feature  │  │ init.sh at start                     │   │\n    │   │ at a time   │  │ clean-state checklist at end          │   │\n    │   │ definition   │  │ handoff note for next session        │   │\n    │   │ of done      │  │ commit only when safe to resume      │   │\n    │   └──────────────┘  └──────────────────────────────────────┘   │\n    │                                                                 │\n    └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\n    The MODEL decides what code to write.\n    The HARNESS governs when, where, and how it writes it.\n    The harness doesn't make the model smarter.\n    It makes the model's output reliable.\nEach subsystem has one job:\nInstructions — Tell the agent what to do, in what order, and what to read before starting. Not one giant file; a progressive disclosure structure the agent navigates on demand.\nState — Track what's been done, what's in progress, and what's next. Persisted to disk so the next session picks up exactly where the last one left off.\nVerification — Only a passing test suite counts as evidence. The agent cannot declare victory without runnable proof.\nScope — Constrain the agent to one feature at a time. No overreach. No half-finishing three things. No rewriting the feature list to hide unfinished work.\nSession Lifecycle — Initialize at the start. Clean up at the end. Leave a clean restart path for the next session.\nWhy This Course Exists\nThe question isn't \"can models write code?\" They can. The question is: can they reliably complete real engineering tasks inside real repositories, over multiple sessions, without constant human supervision?\nRight now, the answer is: not without a harness.\nWITHOUT HARNESS                          WITH HARNESS\n    ==============                          ============\n\n    Session 1: agent writes code            Session 1: agent reads instructions\n              agent breaks tests                      agent runs init.sh\n              agent says \"done\"                       agent works on one feature\n              you fix it manually                     agent verifies before claiming done\n                                                       agent updates progress log\n    Session 2: agent starts fresh                    agent commits clean state\n              agent has no memory\n              of what happened before         Session 2: agent reads progress log\n              agent re-does work                       agent picks up exactly where it left off\n              or does something else entirely          agent continues the unfinished feature\n              you fix it again                         you review, not rescue\n\n    Result: you spend more time                  Result: agent does the work,\n            cleaning up than if you                      you verify the result\n            did it yourself\nThe questions this course actually cares about:\nWhich harness designs improve task completion rates?\nWhich designs reduce rework and incorrect completions?\nWhich mechanisms keep long-running tasks progressing steadily?\nWhich structures keep the system maintainable after multiple agent runs?\nCourse Curriculum & Documentation\nFor the full course materials, please visit the Documentation Website .\nThe curriculum is divided into three parts:\nLectures : 12 conceptual units explaining the theory behind harness engineering.\nProjects : 6 hands-on projects where you build an agentic workspace from scratch.\nResource Library : Copy-ready templates (AGENTS.md, feature_list.json, init.sh, etc.) to use in your own repositories today.\nQuick Start: Improve Your Agent Today\nYou don't need to read all 12 lectures before you start getting value. If you're already using a coding agent on a real project, here's how to improve it right now.\nThe idea is simple: instead of just writing prompts, give your agent a set of structured files that define what to do, what's been done, and how to verify the work. These files live inside your repo, so every session starts from the same state.\nYOUR PROJECT ROOT\n    ├── AGENTS.md              <-- the agent's operating manual\n    ├── CLAUDE.md              <-- (alternative, if using Claude Code)\n    ├── init.sh                <-- runs install + verify + start\n    ├── feature_list.json      <-- what features exist, which are done\n    ├── claude-progress.md     <-- what happened each session\n    └── src/                   <-- your actual code\nGrab the starter templates from the Resource Library and drop them into your project. That's it. Four files, and your agent sessions will already be significantly more stable than running on prompts alone.\nCapstone Project: A Real App\nAll six course projects revolve around the same product: an Electron-based personal knowledge base desktop app.\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n    │               Knowledge Base Desktop App            │\n    │                                                     │\n    │  ┌──────────────┐  ┌──────────────────────────────┐│\n    │  │ Document List │  │       Q&A Panel              ││\n    │  │              │  │                              ││\n    │  │ doc-001.md   │  │  Q: What is harness eng?    ││\n    │  │ doc-002.md   │  │  A: The environment built    ││\n    │  │ doc-003.md   │  │     around an agent model... ││\n    │  │ ...          │  │     [citation: doc-002.md]   ││\n    │  └──────────────┘  └──────────────────────────────┘│\n    │                                                     │\n    │  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐│\n    │  │ Status Bar: 42 docs | 38 indexed | last sync 3m ││\n    │  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘│\n    └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\n    Core features:\n    ├── Import local documents\n    ├── Manage a document library\n    ├── Process and index documents\n    ├── Run AI-powered Q&A over imported content\n    └── Return grounded answers with citations\nThis project was chosen because it combines strong practical value, enough real-world product complexity, and a good setting for observing before/after harness improvements.\nEach course project's starter/solution is a complete copy of this Electron app at that evolutionary stage. P(N+1)'s starter is derived from P(N)'s solution — the app evolves as your harness skills grow.\nLearning Path\nThe course is designed to be done in order. Each phase builds on the last.\nPhase 1: SEE THE PROBLEM              Phase 2: STRUCTURE THE REPO\n    ========================              ==========================\n\n    L01  Strong models ≠ reliable         L03  Repository as single\n         execution                              source of truth\n    L02  What harness actually means\n                                       L04  Split instructions across\n         |                                   files, not one giant file\n         v\n    P01  Prompt-only vs.                       |\n         rules-first comparison                v\n                                               P02  Agent-readable workspace\n\n\n    Phase 3: CONNECT SESSIONS             Phase 4: FEEDBACK & SCOPE\n    ==========================           =========================\n\n    L05  Keep context alive               L07  Draw clear task boundaries\n         across sessions\n                                       L08  Feature lists as harness\n    L06  Initialize before every               primitives\n         agent session\n                                               |\n         |                                     v\n         v                                     P04  Runtime feedback to\n    P03  Multi-session continuity                   correct agent behavior\n\n\n    Phase 5: VERIFICATION                 Phase 6: PUT IT ALL TOGETHER\n    =====================                 ============================\n\n    L09  Stop agents from                 L11  Make agent's runtime\n         declaring victory early               observable\n\n    L10  Full-pipeline run =              L12  Clean handoff at end of\n         real verification                      every session\n\n         |                                     |\n         v                                     v\n    P05  Agent verifies its own work       P06  Build a complete harness\n                                               (capstone project)\nEach phase takes about a week if you're going part-time. If you want to go faster, phases 1–3 can be done in a long weekend.\nSyllabus\nLectures — 12 conceptual units, each answering one core question\nRead the full text for each lecture on the Documentation Website.\nSession Question Core Idea\nL01 Why do strong models still fail on real tasks? The capability gap between benchmarks and real engineering\nL02 What does \"harness\" actually mean? Five subsystems: instructions, state, verification, scope, lifecycle\nL03 Why must the repo be the single source of truth? If the agent can't see it, it doesn't exist\nL04 Why does one giant instruction file fail? Progressive disclosure: give a map, not an encyclopedia\nL05 Why do long-running tasks lose continuity? Persist progress to disk; pick up where you left off\nL06 Why does initialization need its own phase? Verify the environment is healthy before the agent starts work\nL07 Why do agents overreach and under-finish? One feature at a time; explicit definition of done\nL08 Why are feature lists harness primitives? Machine-readable scope boundaries the agent can't ignore\nL09 Why do agents declare victory too early? Verification gaps:"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775800731260}}
{"type":"message","id":"735a8789","parentId":"1a49a8ec","timestamp":"2026-04-10T05:59:04.775Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Great, I now have comprehensive information about Harness Engineering from GitHub. Let me also check the awesome-agent-harness and the skill files from walkinglabs to get a more complete picture.\n\nNow I have enough material to create a comprehensive document about Harness Engineering from GitHub sources. Let me compile this into a well-structured document.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_z223vge8wl1h_1","name":"web_crawl","arguments":{"url":"https://github.com/AutoJunjie/awesome-agent-harness"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"miaoda","model":"miaoda-model-auto","usage":{"input":3616,"output":106,"cacheRead":49275,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":52997,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775800731263,"responseId":"chatcmpl-2c1295ca-f853-47cc-8397-963dee1fc6c0"}}
{"type":"message","id":"97c89f2f","parentId":"735a8789","timestamp":"2026-04-10T05:59:05.187Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_z223vge8wl1h_1","toolName":"web_crawl","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"url\": \"https://github.com/AutoJunjie/awesome-agent-harness\",\n  \"content\": \"AutoJunjie/awesome-agent-harness\\nmain\\nCode\\njhuang and\\njhuang\\nreports\\nreports\\nReplace ASCII art with table in landscape report\\nresearch\\nresearch\\nAdd daily research raw data (JSON)\\nREADME.md\\nREADME.md\\nfix: correct Axon link (axon-core/axon) + add Baton (Go Symphony)\\nREADME\\nAwesome Agent Harness\\nA curated list of tools, frameworks, and resources for agent harness engineering — the discipline of designing environments, constraints, and feedback loops that make AI coding agents reliable at scale.\\nWhat is an Agent Harness?\\nAn agent harness is the infrastructure that wraps around an LLM coding agent. It's everything except the model itself: session management, context delivery, tool design, architectural enforcement, failure recovery, and human oversight.\\nOpenAI's Harness Engineering blog defined the term: \\\"When a software engineering team's primary job is no longer to write code, but to design environments, specify intent, and build feedback loops that allow agents to do reliable work.\\\" Their team built 1M+ lines of production code with zero human-written lines using this approach.\\nAnthropic's Claude Code team discovered the same principles from the tool design side: the harness matters more than the model. Fewer, more expressive tools beat a long menu of narrow ones. Progressive disclosure — letting the agent recursively discover context across layers — outperforms loading everything upfront. \\\"Designing an agent's action space is as much an art as it is a science.\\\"\\nCore Principles\\nFrom the two seminal references above:\\nHumans steer, agents execute — Engineers design environments and review outcomes, not write code\\nRepository knowledge is the system of record — If it's not in the repo, it doesn't exist to the agent. Slack threads, Google Docs, and tribal knowledge are invisible\\nAGENTS.md is a table of contents, not an encyclopedia — Point to deeper sources of truth; don't dump everything in one file\\nEnforce architecture mechanically  — Custom linters, structural tests, and CI checks replace code review for invariants\\nAgent legibility is the goal — Optimize code for agent readability first, human readability second\\nFewer tools, more expressiveness  — Progressive disclosure and composable primitives beat sprawling toolkits\\nSee like an agent — Read the model's outputs, watch where it struggles, and evolve the harness accordingly\\nCorrections are cheap, waiting is expensive — At high agent throughput, fix-forward beats blocking merge gates\\nContents\\nWhat is an Agent Harness?\\nCore Principles\\nFull Lifecycle Platforms\\nAgent Orchestrators\\nTask Runners\\nAgent Harness Frameworks\\nAgent Runtimes\\nCoding Agents\\nRequirements & Spec Tools\\nStandards & Protocols\\nReference & Knowledge\\nContributing\\nFull Lifecycle Platforms\\nTools that span from requirements to delivery with human-in-the-loop approval.\\nChorus — Agent harness for requirements-to-delivery. Task DAGs, sub-agent orchestration (Agent Teams), proof of work, human approval gates. AI proposes, humans verify.\\nGitHub Agentic Workflows — GitHub Actions with coding agent engines (Copilot, Claude Code, Codex). Issue → agent → PR with sandboxing and permissions.\\nAgent Orchestrators\\nOrchestrators solve the throughput problem: at high agent velocity, you need parallel execution with worktree isolation so agents don't step on each other. As OpenAI found, \\\"corrections are cheap, waiting is expensive\\\" — these tools maximize concurrent agent throughput.\\nVibe Kanban — Kanban-based orchestrator with git worktree isolation per agent. Supports 10+ coding agents. Enforces the \\\"one agent, one worktree\\\" pattern that keeps parallel execution clean.\\nEmdash — Open-source Agentic Development Environment (YC W26). Runs parallel agents in isolated worktrees, locally or over SSH — making the \\\"corrections are cheap\\\" principle practical for remote teams.\\nWarp — Agentic development environment built for coding with multiple AI agents.\\nVibeHQ — Orchestrate multiple CLI agents (Claude Code, Codex, Gemini CLI) as a company team.\\nBeehive — Multi-workspace agent orchestrator for parallel issue resolution.\\nAgent Orchestrator — Lightweight orchestrator: ao init --tracker github --agent claude-code --runtime tmux.\\nOh My OpenCode — Performance optimization harness for OpenCode with 44 lifecycle hooks.\\nEverything Claude Code — Skills, instincts, memory, and security harness for Claude Code and Codex.\\nOh My AG — Multi-agent harness for Google Antigravity with 6 specialized agents.\\nTask Runners\\nTask runners bridge the gap between issue trackers and coding agents. They embody the \\\"humans steer, agents execute\\\" principle: a human (or PM agent) creates the issue, the runner spawns an agent, and the output is a PR ready for review.\\nSymphony — OpenAI's reference implementation of harness engineering. A daemon that polls Linear issues, spawns isolated Codex agents per task, and delivers PRs. Embodies \\\"humans steer, agents execute\\\" at scale.\\nBaton — Go implementation of Symphony. Polls Linear for claimable issues, spawns isolated Codex workspaces per issue, streams workflow prompts, and cleans up on completion.\\nLinear Coding Agent Harness — Linear → autonomous coding agent → PR pipeline.\\nGitHub Copilot Coding Agent — Built-in GitHub issue → Copilot agent → PR.\\nAxon — Kubernetes-native framework. Apply a Task CRD, get back a PR and cost in USD. TaskSpawner watches GitHub Issues.\\nDexto — Coding agent and general agent harness for building agentic applications.\\nAgent Harness Frameworks\\nFrameworks for building custom harnesses. Following the principle that \\\"fewer tools, more expressiveness\\\" beats sprawling toolkits, these provide composable primitives rather than opinionated workflows.\\nDeep Agents — Agent harness built on LangChain/LangGraph. Implements progressive disclosure through planning tools and subagent spawning — agents discover context layer by layer rather than loading everything upfront.\\nGambit — Framework for building, running, and verifying LLM workflows.\\nHarness Kit — Patterns and engineering practices for building with AI agents.\\nDesloppify — Agent harness focused on making AI-generated code well-engineered.\\nBridle — TUI/CLI config manager for agent harnesses (Amp, Claude Code, OpenCode, Goose, Copilot CLI, Droid).\\nAgent Runtimes\\nThe persistent infrastructure layer. Agent runtimes give coding agents long-running capabilities they lack natively: persistent memory, cron scheduling, multi-channel messaging, and sub-agent spawning. If orchestrators solve throughput and task runners solve issue-to-PR, runtimes solve \\\"how does an agent stay alive and connected between tasks.\\\"\\nOpenClaw — AI agent runtime. Orchestrates agents across messaging channels with skill system, sub-agent spawning, and persistent session management.\\nZylos Core — Agent runtime adding persistent memory, cron scheduling, multi-channel messaging (Telegram/Feishu), and self-maintenance capabilities to Claude Code agents.\\nCoding Agents\\nThe execution layer. In harness engineering, the agent is a commodity — the harness is the differentiator. These agents write code; everything above them determines whether that code is useful.\\nClaude Code — Anthropic's coding agent. The team's own harness pioneered \\\"seeing like an agent\\\" — progressive disclosure via skill files, fewer composable tools over many narrow ones. Agent Teams enables multi-agent coordination. The Claude Agent SDK extends the harness beyond coding.\\nCodex — OpenAI's coding agent. Cloud and CLI modes.\\nOpenCode — Open-source coding agent with a plugin system (44 lifecycle hooks), server mode HTTP API, and TypeScript SDK. The most extensible harness integration point for custom workflows.\\nGemini CLI — Google's CLI coding agent.\\nKiro CLI — AWS's CLI coding agent with spec-driven workflow.\\nAmp — Sourcegraph's coding agent.\\nCursor Agent CLI — Cursor's command-line agent mode.\\nGitHub Copilot CLI — GitHub's CLI coding agent.\\nAider — AI pair programming in your terminal.\\nRequirements & Spec Tools\\nThe planning layer addresses the biggest harness gap: agents can write code, but someone has to decide what to build. \\\"Repository knowledge is the system of record\\\" — these tools generate the specs and requirements that agents consume.\\nKiro IDE — AWS's spec-driven development IDE. Generates structured specs and manages requirements.\\nOpenSpec — Spec-driven development CLI. Generate structured specs from natural language.\\nSpec Kit — GitHub's spec generation toolkit.\\nagents.md — Open standard for project-level agent instructions. Following the principle that \\\"AGENTS.md is a table of contents, not an encyclopedia\\\" — it should point to deeper sources of truth.\\nPencil — MCP-enabled design canvas inside VSCode/Cursor. Design files live in the repo under Git version control, bridging visual spec to code generation. Closed source.\\nOpen Pencil — Open-source AI-native design editor (MIT). 75+ tools and an MCP server let coding agents read/write .fig files headlessly.\\nStandards & Protocols\\nMCP (Model Context Protocol) — Open standard for connecting AI models to external tools and data sources.\\nagents.md — Open standard for project-level agent configuration.\\nAGENTS.md — OpenAI's convention for repository-level agent instructions.\\nACP (Agent Communication Protocol) — Open protocol for agent-to-agent and agent-to-harness communication. Enables interoperability across coding agents and orchestrators.\\nReference & Knowledge\\nSeminal References\\nHarness Engineering: Leveraging Codex in an Agent-First World — OpenAI's defining blog post. How they built 1M+ lines with zero human-written code. Introduced the concepts of repository knowledge as system of record, progressive context disclosure, and mechanical architecture enforcement.\\nLessons from Building Claude Code: Seeing Like an Agent — Thariq (Claude Code lead) on designing agent action spaces. Fewer tools beat more tools. Progressive disclosure outperforms upfront loading. The harness must evolve with the model.\\nBuilding Effective Agents — Anthropic's guide: simple, composable patterns beat complex frameworks.\\nArticles\\nBuilding an AI-Native Engineering Team — OpenAI's guide to structuring teams around AI-first workflows.\\nThe Emerging \\\"Harness Engineering\\\" Playbook — How OpenAI is retooling engineering teams.\\nConductors to Orchestrators: The Future of Agentic Coding — O'Reilly overview of the orchestration landscape.\\nMy LLM Coding Workflow Going into 2026 — Addy Osmani's specs-first approach.\\nHow the Claude Code Team Designs Agent Tools — Analysis of progressive disclosure and tool subtraction in agent design.\\nTalks\\nThe Future of Coding is Agents — Andrej Karpathy (YC) — Landmark talk on the trajectory from assistants to agents.\\nAgentic Coding — Armin Ronacher  — Creator of Flask on adopting agentic workflows in practice.\\n12 Rules of Harness Engineering — Practical rules derived from OpenAI's approach.\\nDocumentation Patterns\\nagent-harness — Principles, checklists, and invariants for AI coding workflows.\\nharness-kit — Engineering patterns for building with AI agents.\\nContributing\\nContributions welcome! When suggesting additions, include:\\nA one-line description of what the tool does\\nWhy it belongs in this list (which layer of the stack it addresses)\\n\"\n}"}],"details":{"url":"https://github.com/AutoJunjie/awesome-agent-harness","content":"AutoJunjie/awesome-agent-harness\nmain\nCode\njhuang and\njhuang\nreports\nreports\nReplace ASCII art with table in landscape report\nresearch\nresearch\nAdd daily research raw data (JSON)\nREADME.md\nREADME.md\nfix: correct Axon link (axon-core/axon) + add Baton (Go Symphony)\nREADME\nAwesome Agent Harness\nA curated list of tools, frameworks, and resources for agent harness engineering — the discipline of designing environments, constraints, and feedback loops that make AI coding agents reliable at scale.\nWhat is an Agent Harness?\nAn agent harness is the infrastructure that wraps around an LLM coding agent. It's everything except the model itself: session management, context delivery, tool design, architectural enforcement, failure recovery, and human oversight.\nOpenAI's Harness Engineering blog defined the term: \"When a software engineering team's primary job is no longer to write code, but to design environments, specify intent, and build feedback loops that allow agents to do reliable work.\" Their team built 1M+ lines of production code with zero human-written lines using this approach.\nAnthropic's Claude Code team discovered the same principles from the tool design side: the harness matters more than the model. Fewer, more expressive tools beat a long menu of narrow ones. Progressive disclosure — letting the agent recursively discover context across layers — outperforms loading everything upfront. \"Designing an agent's action space is as much an art as it is a science.\"\nCore Principles\nFrom the two seminal references above:\nHumans steer, agents execute — Engineers design environments and review outcomes, not write code\nRepository knowledge is the system of record — If it's not in the repo, it doesn't exist to the agent. Slack threads, Google Docs, and tribal knowledge are invisible\nAGENTS.md is a table of contents, not an encyclopedia — Point to deeper sources of truth; don't dump everything in one file\nEnforce architecture mechanically  — Custom linters, structural tests, and CI checks replace code review for invariants\nAgent legibility is the goal — Optimize code for agent readability first, human readability second\nFewer tools, more expressiveness  — Progressive disclosure and composable primitives beat sprawling toolkits\nSee like an agent — Read the model's outputs, watch where it struggles, and evolve the harness accordingly\nCorrections are cheap, waiting is expensive — At high agent throughput, fix-forward beats blocking merge gates\nContents\nWhat is an Agent Harness?\nCore Principles\nFull Lifecycle Platforms\nAgent Orchestrators\nTask Runners\nAgent Harness Frameworks\nAgent Runtimes\nCoding Agents\nRequirements & Spec Tools\nStandards & Protocols\nReference & Knowledge\nContributing\nFull Lifecycle Platforms\nTools that span from requirements to delivery with human-in-the-loop approval.\nChorus — Agent harness for requirements-to-delivery. Task DAGs, sub-agent orchestration (Agent Teams), proof of work, human approval gates. AI proposes, humans verify.\nGitHub Agentic Workflows — GitHub Actions with coding agent engines (Copilot, Claude Code, Codex). Issue → agent → PR with sandboxing and permissions.\nAgent Orchestrators\nOrchestrators solve the throughput problem: at high agent velocity, you need parallel execution with worktree isolation so agents don't step on each other. As OpenAI found, \"corrections are cheap, waiting is expensive\" — these tools maximize concurrent agent throughput.\nVibe Kanban — Kanban-based orchestrator with git worktree isolation per agent. Supports 10+ coding agents. Enforces the \"one agent, one worktree\" pattern that keeps parallel execution clean.\nEmdash — Open-source Agentic Development Environment (YC W26). Runs parallel agents in isolated worktrees, locally or over SSH — making the \"corrections are cheap\" principle practical for remote teams.\nWarp — Agentic development environment built for coding with multiple AI agents.\nVibeHQ — Orchestrate multiple CLI agents (Claude Code, Codex, Gemini CLI) as a company team.\nBeehive — Multi-workspace agent orchestrator for parallel issue resolution.\nAgent Orchestrator — Lightweight orchestrator: ao init --tracker github --agent claude-code --runtime tmux.\nOh My OpenCode — Performance optimization harness for OpenCode with 44 lifecycle hooks.\nEverything Claude Code — Skills, instincts, memory, and security harness for Claude Code and Codex.\nOh My AG — Multi-agent harness for Google Antigravity with 6 specialized agents.\nTask Runners\nTask runners bridge the gap between issue trackers and coding agents. They embody the \"humans steer, agents execute\" principle: a human (or PM agent) creates the issue, the runner spawns an agent, and the output is a PR ready for review.\nSymphony — OpenAI's reference implementation of harness engineering. A daemon that polls Linear issues, spawns isolated Codex agents per task, and delivers PRs. Embodies \"humans steer, agents execute\" at scale.\nBaton — Go implementation of Symphony. Polls Linear for claimable issues, spawns isolated Codex workspaces per issue, streams workflow prompts, and cleans up on completion.\nLinear Coding Agent Harness — Linear → autonomous coding agent → PR pipeline.\nGitHub Copilot Coding Agent — Built-in GitHub issue → Copilot agent → PR.\nAxon — Kubernetes-native framework. Apply a Task CRD, get back a PR and cost in USD. TaskSpawner watches GitHub Issues.\nDexto — Coding agent and general agent harness for building agentic applications.\nAgent Harness Frameworks\nFrameworks for building custom harnesses. Following the principle that \"fewer tools, more expressiveness\" beats sprawling toolkits, these provide composable primitives rather than opinionated workflows.\nDeep Agents — Agent harness built on LangChain/LangGraph. Implements progressive disclosure through planning tools and subagent spawning — agents discover context layer by layer rather than loading everything upfront.\nGambit — Framework for building, running, and verifying LLM workflows.\nHarness Kit — Patterns and engineering practices for building with AI agents.\nDesloppify — Agent harness focused on making AI-generated code well-engineered.\nBridle — TUI/CLI config manager for agent harnesses (Amp, Claude Code, OpenCode, Goose, Copilot CLI, Droid).\nAgent Runtimes\nThe persistent infrastructure layer. Agent runtimes give coding agents long-running capabilities they lack natively: persistent memory, cron scheduling, multi-channel messaging, and sub-agent spawning. If orchestrators solve throughput and task runners solve issue-to-PR, runtimes solve \"how does an agent stay alive and connected between tasks.\"\nOpenClaw — AI agent runtime. Orchestrates agents across messaging channels with skill system, sub-agent spawning, and persistent session management.\nZylos Core — Agent runtime adding persistent memory, cron scheduling, multi-channel messaging (Telegram/Feishu), and self-maintenance capabilities to Claude Code agents.\nCoding Agents\nThe execution layer. In harness engineering, the agent is a commodity — the harness is the differentiator. These agents write code; everything above them determines whether that code is useful.\nClaude Code — Anthropic's coding agent. The team's own harness pioneered \"seeing like an agent\" — progressive disclosure via skill files, fewer composable tools over many narrow ones. Agent Teams enables multi-agent coordination. The Claude Agent SDK extends the harness beyond coding.\nCodex — OpenAI's coding agent. Cloud and CLI modes.\nOpenCode — Open-source coding agent with a plugin system (44 lifecycle hooks), server mode HTTP API, and TypeScript SDK. The most extensible harness integration point for custom workflows.\nGemini CLI — Google's CLI coding agent.\nKiro CLI — AWS's CLI coding agent with spec-driven workflow.\nAmp — Sourcegraph's coding agent.\nCursor Agent CLI — Cursor's command-line agent mode.\nGitHub Copilot CLI — GitHub's CLI coding agent.\nAider — AI pair programming in your terminal.\nRequirements & Spec Tools\nThe planning layer addresses the biggest harness gap: agents can write code, but someone has to decide what to build. \"Repository knowledge is the system of record\" — these tools generate the specs and requirements that agents consume.\nKiro IDE — AWS's spec-driven development IDE. Generates structured specs and manages requirements.\nOpenSpec — Spec-driven development CLI. Generate structured specs from natural language.\nSpec Kit — GitHub's spec generation toolkit.\nagents.md — Open standard for project-level agent instructions. Following the principle that \"AGENTS.md is a table of contents, not an encyclopedia\" — it should point to deeper sources of truth.\nPencil — MCP-enabled design canvas inside VSCode/Cursor. Design files live in the repo under Git version control, bridging visual spec to code generation. Closed source.\nOpen Pencil — Open-source AI-native design editor (MIT). 75+ tools and an MCP server let coding agents read/write .fig files headlessly.\nStandards & Protocols\nMCP (Model Context Protocol) — Open standard for connecting AI models to external tools and data sources.\nagents.md — Open standard for project-level agent configuration.\nAGENTS.md — OpenAI's convention for repository-level agent instructions.\nACP (Agent Communication Protocol) — Open protocol for agent-to-agent and agent-to-harness communication. Enables interoperability across coding agents and orchestrators.\nReference & Knowledge\nSeminal References\nHarness Engineering: Leveraging Codex in an Agent-First World — OpenAI's defining blog post. How they built 1M+ lines with zero human-written code. Introduced the concepts of repository knowledge as system of record, progressive context disclosure, and mechanical architecture enforcement.\nLessons from Building Claude Code: Seeing Like an Agent — Thariq (Claude Code lead) on designing agent action spaces. Fewer tools beat more tools. Progressive disclosure outperforms upfront loading. The harness must evolve with the model.\nBuilding Effective Agents — Anthropic's guide: simple, composable patterns beat complex frameworks.\nArticles\nBuilding an AI-Native Engineering Team — OpenAI's guide to structuring teams around AI-first workflows.\nThe Emerging \"Harness Engineering\" Playbook — How OpenAI is retooling engineering teams.\nConductors to Orchestrators: The Future of Agentic Coding — O'Reilly overview of the orchestration landscape.\nMy LLM Coding Workflow Going into 2026 — Addy Osmani's specs-first approach.\nHow the Claude Code Team Designs Agent Tools — Analysis of progressive disclosure and tool subtraction in agent design.\nTalks\nThe Future of Coding is Agents — Andrej Karpathy (YC) — Landmark talk on the trajectory from assistants to agents.\nAgentic Coding — Armin Ronacher  — Creator of Flask on adopting agentic workflows in practice.\n12 Rules of Harness Engineering — Practical rules derived from OpenAI's approach.\nDocumentation Patterns\nagent-harness — Principles, checklists, and invariants for AI coding workflows.\nharness-kit — Engineering patterns for building with AI agents.\nContributing\nContributions welcome! When suggesting additions, include:\nA one-line description of what the tool does\nWhy it belongs in this list (which layer of the stack it addresses)\n"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775800745186}}
{"type":"custom","customType":"openclaw:prompt-error","data":{"timestamp":1775800809784,"runId":"b76a0ce5-d79e-4fab-8b56-1833ecce9322","sessionId":"6796ab0c-0627-4966-b5bf-e34fc0b88ab2","provider":"miaoda","model":"miaoda-model-auto","api":"openai-completions","error":"aborted"},"id":"6ba4b5e8","parentId":"97c89f2f","timestamp":"2026-04-10T06:00:09.784Z"}
{"type":"message","id":"cc388e6b","parentId":"6ba4b5e8","timestamp":"2026-04-10T06:00:09.785Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have comprehensive information about Harness Engineering from GitHub. Let me compile everything into a comprehensive document and save it.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"内容充足了，现在整合所有资料，生成完整的学习文档。\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_vgmqzqlyowvu_1","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"# Harness 工程深度学习笔记\n\n> 来源：GitHub 社区资料整合\n> 参考：\n> - [celesteanders/harness-engineering-best-practices](https://gist.github.com/celesteanders/21edad2367c8ede2ff092bd87e56a26f)（Anthropic + OpenAI 最佳实践）\n> - [walkinglabs/learn-harness-engineering](https://github.com/walkinglabs/learn-harness-engineering)（系统课程）\n> - [AutoJunjie/awesome-agent-harness](https://github.com/AutoJunjie/awesome-agent-harness)（工具与框架全景图）\n\n---\n\n## 一、核心定义\n\n**Agent Harness（代理马具）** 是包裹在 LLM 编程智能体周围的全部基础设施——除了模型本身的一切：会话管理、上下文传递、工具设计、架构约束、故障恢复、人工监督。\n\n> \"当软件工程团队的主要工作不再是写代码，而是设计环境、指定意图、构建反馈循环，让智能体可靠地工作时——这就是 Harness 工程。\" — OpenAI\n\n**关键认知：模型是商品，Harness 才是差异所在。**\n\n---\n\n## 二、核心原则（9条）\n\n1. **上下文窗口是约束，结构化产物是解决方案。** 一切都是为了弥合会话之间的鸿沟。\n2. **分离生成与评估。** 智能体无法客观评价自己的工作。\n3. **一次一任务。** 专注防止上下文耗尽，保持会话可恢复。\n4. **先验证再构建。** 始终检查上一个会话是否破坏了现有功能。\n5. **接入快速反馈循环。** 测试、linter、类型检查、UI 自动化作为反压机制。\n6. **仓库是唯一真实来源。** 不在仓库里，智能体就看不到。\n7. **人类掌舵，智能体执行。** 工程师设计环境、指定意图、构建反馈循环，智能体写代码。\n8. **期待最终一致性。** 大多数问题可以通过更好的 prompt 循环解决。\n9. **极致简化。** 去掉智能体不再需要的复杂度。\n\n---\n\n## 三、五大子系统\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│                    THE HARNESS                      │\n│                                                      │\n│  ┌────────────┐  ┌────────────┐  ┌────────────────┐  │\n│  │  Instructions│  │   State    │  │  Verification │  │\n│  │            │  │            │  │                │  │\n│  │ AGENTS.md  │  │progress.md │  │ tests + lint   │  │\n│  │ feature_   │  │feature_    │  │ type-check     │  │\n│  │ list.json  │  │list.json   │  │ smoke runs     │  │\n│  │ docs/      │  │git log     │  │ e2e pipeline   │  │\n│  └────────────┘  └────────────┘  └────────────────┘  │\n│                                                      │\n│  ┌────────────┐  ┌────────────────────────────────┐  │\n│  │   Scope    │  │      Session Lifecycle          │  │\n│  │            │  │                                 │  │\n│  │ one feature│  │ init.sh at start                 │  │\n│  │ at a time  │  │ clean-state checklist at end    │  │\n│  │ definition │  │ handoff note for next session   │  │\n│  │ of done    │  │ commit only when safe to resume│  │\n│  └────────────┘  └────────────────────────────────┘  │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### 1. Instructions（指令系统）\n\n**核心思想：做地图，不要做百科全书。**\n\n- AGENTS.md / CLAUDE.md 应保持约 100 行，作为目录指向更深层的真实来源\n- 一个巨型指令文件会挤占任务空间，且快速腐坏\n- 按需渐进披露：智能体从一个小而稳定的入口开始，被告知去哪里查找\n\n### 2. State（状态管理）\n\n**核心思想：智能体的上下文窗口是短暂的，一切必须写入磁盘。**\n\n必持久化的文件：\n- **feature_list.json**：任务清单，JSON 格式（比 Markdown 更抗模型破坏），永不删除/重排序项目，只将状态从 incomplete 改为 complete\n- **progress.md**：每次会话结束时写，记录完成了什么、发现/修复了什么 bug、下一步做什么\n- **plan/spec 文件**：原始需求，放在项目目录供智能体参考\n- **init/setup.sh**：自动化环境安装\n- **Git 历史**：描述性 commit 是恢复机制，智能体在会话开始时读取近期 commit\n\n### 3. Verification（验证系统）\n\n**核心思想：只有通过测试套件才算证据。智能体不能在没有可运行证明的情况下宣告胜利。**\n\n- 类型检查器、linter、测试套件、静态分析、安全扫描作为反压机制\n- 反馈轮转必须快，慢验证减少智能体可尝试的迭代次数\n- 使用浏览器/UI 自动化（Puppeteer / Playwright MCP）验证——智能体往往会在没有强制情况下跳过实际测试\n- 构建带具体评分标准的 evaluator，定义\"好\"的具体样子，提供 few-shot 示例校准\n\n### 4. Scope（范围控制）\n\n**核心思想：一次一任务，不越界，不半途而废。**\n\n- 防止上下文耗尽和会话不可恢复\n- 用 feature_list.json 定义 done，不允许智能体通过重写 feature list 隐藏未完成工作\n- 宽松条件：项目成熟且智能体展示可靠性后可放宽；质量下降时收紧\n\n### 5. Session Lifecycle（会话生命周期）\n\n每个会话遵循可预测的序列：\n\n1. **Orient（定向）** — 读 progress notes、feature list、近期 git 历史\n2. **Setup（初始化）** — 运行 init.sh 启动开发服务器 / 前置条件\n3. **Verify baseline（验证基线）** — 测试现有功能仍正常，再触碰新代码\n4. **Select one task（选一个任务）** — 挑最高优先级的未完成项\n5. **Implement（实现）** — 构建功能\n6. **Test（测试）** — 通过实际 UI/API 验证，不只是单元测试\n7. **Update state（更新状态）** — 标记任务完成，描述性 commit，写 progress notes\n8. **Clean exit（干净退出）** — 确认应用处于工作状态\n\n---\n\n## 四、多智能体模式\n\n### 分离的智能体角色\n\n| 角色 | 职责 |\n|---|---|\n| **Planner** | 将短 prompt 扩展为完整产品规格，关注产品和高层技术设计，不过早指定实现细节 |\n| **Generator/Builder** | 按 spec 一次实现一个功能，专注增量开发 |\n| **Evaluator/QA** | 以用户角度测试应用，根据标准评分，将具体反馈发送回 Generator 迭代 |\n\n> \"将工作的智能体与评判工作的智能体分离，是一个强有力的杠杆——因为让评估者变得更加怀疑，远比让生成者变得更加自我批判要容易得多。\" — Anthropic\n\n### 何时引入多智能体\n\n**保持单体，直到复杂度要求才拆分。** 多智能体系统引入的复杂度与微服务相当，还叠加了非决定性。只有当单智能体遇到特定天花板时，才增加智能体。\n\n---\n\n## 五、安全与沙箱（三层防御）\n\n```\n1. OS级沙箱 —— 隔离智能体的执行环境\n2. 文件系统限制 —— 只允许在项目目录内操作文件\n3. 命令白名单 —— 只允许智能体需要的命令\n   用 shlex 解析命令，处理管道/链式操作\n   敏感命令加验证（如 pkill 只对 dev 进程生效）\n```\n\n---\n\n## 六、上下文窗口管理策略\n\n- **子智能体并行化**：将只读操作（搜索、分析）分配给子智能体，主上下文窗口作为调度器\n- **确定性地在每次循环加载相同的核心文件**：plan 和 specs 每次迭代都加载\n- **搜索后再实现**：用 ripgrep 搜索再实现，避免重复实现\n- **用子智能体总结结果**，不要把原始输出塞进主上下文\n\n---\n\n## 七、Git 是安全网\n\n- 每次成功任务后 commit，附描述性消息\n- 会话开始时读取近期 git 历史\n- 用 git tag 标记已知良好状态\n- 当智能体产出损坏的代码库时，`git reset --hard` 到上一个良好状态然后重跑\n- 期待失败，提前计划应对\n\n---\n\n## 八、Harness 的演进\n\n> \"Harness 中的每个组件都编码了关于模型自身无法做到什么的假设。随着模型改进，这些假设会过时。\"\n\n每次模型升级时：\n- 剥离不再承重的脚手架\n- 增加实现之前不可能实现能力的新组件\n- 一次移除一个组件并评估影响\n\n---\n\n## 九、开源工具生态全景图\n\n### 全生命周期平台\n- **Chorus** — 需求到交付的 Agent Harness，含任务 DAG、子"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"miaoda","model":"miaoda-model-auto","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"aborted","timestamp":1775800745188,"responseId":"chatcmpl-4a10db51-bdbf-422b-b23f-7d9c18fe1337","errorMessage":"Request was aborted"}}
